Let's think step by step. To represent a line using linear equations, we need two equations with different variables. For our first line, we have $2x=3y=-z$. For our second line, we have $6x=-y=-4z$. Notice that both lines involve $x$, but one uses $3y$ while the other uses just $y$. To make them comparable, let's isolate $y$ in the first equation: $y = \dfrac{2}{3}x$. Now, both lines involve $x$ and $y$. Let's set up a system of linear equations:
\begin{align*}
6x & = -y \\
-y & = -\dfrac{2}{3}x && (\text{Using } y = \dfrac{2}{3}x)
\end{align*}
Therefore, our second line is defined by the system of linear equations:
\begin{align*}
6x & = -y \\
y & = -\dfrac{2}{3}x && (\text{Setting } y = -\dfrac{2}{3}x \text{ in the second equation})
\end
